('daubert-standard', 'Daubert Standard', 'legal_standard',
'Federal Rule of Evidence 702 gatekeeping test establishing admissibility of expert testimony based on testability, peer review, error rate, standards, and general acceptance.',
'The Daubert standard emerged from Daubert v. Merrell Dow Pharmaceuticals, Inc., 509 U.S. 579 (1993), which fundamentally reshaped federal expert testimony law. Rather than applying the Frye "general acceptance" test, the Supreme Court held that FRE 702 requires courts to assess the reliability of the underlying methodology itself. The five Daubert factors—(1) testability/falsifiability; (2) peer review and publication; (3) known or potential error rate; (4) controlling standards and protocols; (5) general acceptance—are not a rigid checklist but a flexible inquiry tailored to the expert''s field.

In toxic-tort litigation, Daubert gatekeeping directly impacts epidemiological testimony, dose-response modeling, biomarker interpretation, and mechanistic causation evidence. The Kumho Tire Co. v. Carmichael, 526 U.S. 137 (1999) trilogy extension clarified that the test applies to all expert testimony, not just science-based opinions. General Electric Co. v. Joiner, 522 U.S. 136 (1997), established that appellate courts review gatekeeping decisions for abuse of discretion, giving trial courts substantial deference.

Post-2000 amendments to FRE 702 codified Daubert factors into statutory language: "scientific . . . knowledge will help the trier of fact . . . [based on] sufficient facts or data . . . [using] reliable principles and methods . . . [properly] applied to the facts." This shift from judge-as-scientist to judge-as-gatekeeper does not immunize sloppy science; courts regularly exclude testimony failing the reliability prong.

State courts have adopted Daubert (NY, CA, TX, IL, PA, NJ, MA, WA, MI) or retained Frye (a shrinking minority), but federal litigation—the bulk of mass-tort discovery—applies Daubert uniformly. Recent appellate scrutiny has tightened: courts are skeptical of extrapolation from high-dose animal studies to low-dose human exposure without mechanistic bridge.',
'Every toxicology expert disclosure in federal court invites a Daubert challenge. Opposing counsel will dissect methodology, probe error rates, demand published protocols, and argue the application to your plaintiff is speculative or extrapolated beyond peer-reviewed bounds. Anticipate attacks on dose-response assumptions, biomarker specificity, and "gulf between study conditions and actual exposure." The bar is admissibility, not credibility; pass Daubert and the jury decides weight. Failure is case-dispositive.',
'Daubert challenges succeed most often on prong (1) testability—specifically, whether a dose-response or biomarker threshold was pre-specified or reverse-engineered post-hoc—and prong (4) standards, when the expert''s protocol deviates from published epidemiological guidance. Recent federal practice shows heightened skepticism of expert extrapolation: courts demand statistically adequate sample sizes and peer-reviewed support for the leap from group-level (general causation) to individual (specific causation) claims.',
'{"cases": [{"citation": "Daubert v. Merrell Dow Pharmaceuticals, Inc., 509 U.S. 579 (1993)", "ratio": "Reliability inquiry replaces Frye general-acceptance test; five-factor approach"}, {"citation": "Kumho Tire Co. v. Carmichael, 526 U.S. 137 (1999)", "ratio": "Daubert applies beyond pure science to specialized knowledge and engineering"}, {"citation": "General Electric Co. v. Joiner, 522 U.S. 136 (1997)", "ratio": "Abuse-of-discretion standard for appellate review; substantial deference to trial court"}, {"citation": "Crane Co. v. DeLisle, 258 So. 3d 1219 (Fla. 2018)", "ratio": "Reversed Daubert exclusion; industrial hygienist opinion on every-exposure causation admissible under Florida law"}, {"citation": "In re Lipitor (Atorvastatin Calcium) Products Liability Litigation, 892 F.3d 624 (4th Cir. 2018)", "ratio": "Excluded general-causation testimony as speculative; error rate and dose-response foundation required"}]}',
ARRAY['FRE 702 gatekeeping', 'reliability standard', 'expert admissibility threshold'],
ARRAY['frye-standard', 'fre-702', 'general-causation', 'specific-causation']
),

('frye-standard', 'Frye Standard', 'legal_standard',
'1923 federal test for expert testimony based on general acceptance of the methodology in the relevant scientific community. Still controlling in minority of state courts.',
'Frye v. United States, 293 F. 1013 (D.C. Cir. 1923), established a single gatekeeping question: Is the proffered scientific principle or discovery "sufficiently established to have gained general acceptance in the particular field in which it belongs?" This general-acceptance test preceded Daubert by 70 years and remains the controlling standard in a handful of state jurisdictions (New York, California pre-1995, Illinois, New Jersey, Pennsylvania, Washington state).

Under Frye, the focus is narrow: peer-reviewed acceptance within the relevant scientific field. There is no explicit multi-factor balancing; the court asks whether the methodology has crossed a threshold of reliability through consensus. Frye is more conservative in some respects (requiring genuine consensus) and more rigid in others (no flexibility for novel but reliable methods that lack time-tested acceptance).

In toxic-tort practice, Frye has become jurisdictionally important. New York state courts still apply Frye to toxicology testimony; recent cases denying admission of biomarker evidence for specific causation hinge on failure to show "general acceptance" of the biomarker as predictive in that particular disease state. Pennsylvania and Washington courts similarly scrutinize epidemiological methodology and mechanistic testimony under the Frye lens.

The key strategic distinction: under Frye, you must show the scientific community has vetted and accepted the method, not merely that the method *could* work or that one expert has found it reliable. Absence of published commentary or replication weakens the Frye case. Conversely, if your method is published in high-impact journals and cited by dozens of peers, Frye becomes easier to satisfy.

Frye does not override itself for "new" science; courts in Frye jurisdictions have excluded novel molecular biomarkers as not yet generally accepted, even when mechanistically sound and preliminarily validated. The standard rewards methodological conservatism.',
'If your trial is in a Frye jurisdiction, your toxicology expert must affirmatively demonstrate that peer-reviewed literature and consensus among practicing toxicologists accept the methodology as sufficiently reliable. A single published paper is insufficient; opposing counsel will argue it''s an outlier. You need multiple independent replication, citation in textbooks, and ideally testimony from peers that the field considers it settled science. Frye is harder to clear for novel-but-sound methods; Daubert is harder to clear for sloppy methodology applied to edge cases.',
'Frye challenges rarely cite specific error-rate or standard-protocols data; instead they attack the expert''s assertion of "general acceptance." Discovery demands lists of scientific societies, textbooks, and corroborating publications. If your field has divided opinion, Frye claims fail. Recent Frye-jurisdiction cases show courts deferring to professional societies (e.g., ACGIH for occupational exposure limits) as proxies for "general acceptance."',
'{"cases": [{"citation": "Frye v. United States, 293 F. 1013 (D.C. Cir. 1923)", "ratio": "General-acceptance test: sufficiently established to have gained general acceptance in the particular field"}, {"citation": "People v. Leahy, 8 Cal.4th 587 (1994)", "ratio": "California adopted Daubert, rejecting Frye"}, {"citation": "State v. Ford, 158 N.J. 599 (1999)", "ratio": "New Jersey continues to apply Frye standard to scientific evidence"}]}',
