('fre-702', 'Federal Rule of Evidence 702', 'legal_standard',
'Post-2000 statutory codification of Daubert factors: expert testimony admissible if scientific knowledge, reliable methodology/principles, and reliable application assist the trier of fact.',
'Federal Rule of Evidence 702, amended in 2000 to incorporate Daubert principles and again in 2023 to emphasize gatekeeping rigor, reads: "A witness who is qualified as an expert by knowledge, skill, experience, training, or education may testify in the form of an opinion or otherwise if: (a) the expert''s scientific, technical, or other specialized knowledge will help the trier of fact to understand the evidence or to determine a fact in issue; (b) the testimony is based on sufficient facts or data; (c) the testimony is the product of reliable principles and methods; and (d) the expert has reliably applied the principles and methods to the facts of the case."

This statutory language operationalizes Daubert''s multi-factor inquiry. The four prongs are conjunctive: all must be satisfied for admissibility. Prong (c)—reliability of principles and methods—is the gatekeeper inquiry; prong (d)—reliable application—is where courts scrutinize whether the expert''s reasoning chain is valid and not speculative.

In toxic-tort litigation, FRE 702 is the federal baseline. Courts invoke it when excluding exposure-reconstruction testimony (insufficient data to support dose estimates), dose-response extrapolation (unexplained leap from animal studies to human low-dose risk), and differential-diagnosis opinions (failure to rule out alternative etiologies). The 2023 amendment heightened judicial gatekeeping: advisory committee notes emphasize that "preliminary questions" under FRE 104(a) do not shield unreliable opinions; the judge must affirmatively find reliability.

Distinguish admissibility (FRE 702 pass) from weight and credibility (jury determination). An expert can pass FRE 702 and still be impeached, contradicted, or given little weight by the jury; non-admission is the far more severe consequence. Federal courts increasingly apply FRE 702 strictly in mass-tort discovery, particularly when plaintiffs'' experts rely on extrapolation, assumptions about bioavailability, or population-level data applied to individual causation without mechanistic bridge.',
'Your disclosure must anticipate FRE 702 scrutiny of all four prongs: Is the knowledge scientific or speculative? (prong a); does the expert rely on sufficient facts or guesswork? (prong b); are the principles and methods published and tested? (prong c); has the expert actually applied them logically to *this plaintiff*, or merely asserted conclusions? (prong d). Defense motions to exclude will cherry-pick ambiguities in prongs (b) and (d). Pre-emptive narrative and explicit methodology in the report defang such attacks.',
'Prong (c) "reliable principles and methods" fails most often when the expert relies on a single published paper, animal studies without mechanistic bridge to humans, or proprietary algorithms lacking peer-review. Prong (d) "reliable application" fails when the expert''s dose-response model uses inputs not supported by cited literature or when differential diagnosis omits plausible competing etiologies. Recent circuit decisions exclude testimony under prongs (c)/(d) without detailed error-rate discussion, implying that general implausibility suffices to filter unreliable application.',
'{"rules": [{"citation": "Federal Rule of Evidence 702 (2000 Amendment & 2023 Amendment)", "text": "Four-prong test: scientific knowledge, sufficient facts/data, reliable principles/methods, reliable application. 2023 Amendment advisory notes emphasize gatekeeping rigor."}]}',
ARRAY['FRE 702 gatekeeping', 'expert admissibility', 'Daubert statutory codification'],
