('every-exposure-doctrine', 'Every Exposure Doctrine', 'concept',
'Theory in fiber-disease litigation: each and every exposure above background contributes to cumulative disease risk. Jurisdiction-dependent; some courts reject as scientifically unsound, others admit if supported by cohort and mechanistic evidence.',
'The "every-exposure doctrine" is a causation theory most prominent in asbestos, silica, and occupational lung-disease litigation. It posits that *any* exposure to a respirable fiber above ambient background increases disease risk cumulatively; no exposure is "safe," and thus any defendant exposing the plaintiff to any amount of asbestos bears potential liability. This contrasts with threshold-based theories.

The doctrine emerged from asbestos epidemiology, particularly research showing that occupational cohorts all exhibited elevated mesothelioma risk, with no clear dose floor. Defense toxicologists counter that the epidemiological data is confounded, that animal studies show mesothelioma follows a threshold dose, and that the "every exposure" framing is biologically implausible.

State courts are split. Florida Supreme Court, in Crane Co. v. DeLisle, 258 So. 3d 1219 (Fla. 2018), upheld a jury verdict based partly on expert testimony applying the every-exposure doctrine, reversing the trial court''s Daubert exclusion. The expert, Dr. Myron Dahlgren, testified that a 10-year cumulative occupational exposure to asbestos-containing insulation was capable of causing mesothelioma even at exposure levels below OSHA regulatory thresholds. Pennsylvania, Texas, and several federal circuits have rejected the doctrine as unsupported speculation.

The strategic distinction: if your jurisdiction accepts the every-exposure doctrine and your expert can cite supportive cohort data and mechanistic plausibility, causation is easier. If your jurisdiction rejects it, the burden is higher—you must show the plaintiff''s cumulative dose exceeded published NOAEL/LOAEL estimates.',
'The every-exposure doctrine is jurisdiction-specific gold or poison. Before relying on it, research your state''s appellate posture: does the court accept cumulative-exposure causation theories absent a quantified dose-response threshold? If yes, emphasize your expert''s reliance on published occupational cohort data and mechanistic coherence. If your jurisdiction rejects the doctrine, pivot to traditional specific-causation: quantify the plaintiff''s cumulative dose, apply published NOAEL/LOAEL data, and show the plaintiff''s exposure exceeded the no-effect threshold. Crane v. DeLisle is your gold standard if the case is in Florida.',
'Every-exposure-doctrine testimony triggers intense FRE 702(c) scrutiny: Is the methodology published and peer-reviewed, or is it an ad-hoc assertion? Daubert challenges demand that the expert cite the specific epidemiological studies supporting cumulative-exposure causation, explain their sample sizes and control for confounders, and address why animal studies showing threshold doses are distinguishable. Courts increasingly exclude every-exposure opinions as speculative when the expert fails to quantify dose or distinguish the plaintiff''s exposure profile from background.',
'{"cases": [{"citation": "Crane Co. v. DeLisle, 258 So. 3d 1219 (Fla. 2018)", "ratio": "Affirmed every-exposure doctrine when expert opinion supported by occupational cohort data and mechanistic plausibility; Daubert exclusion reversed"}, {"citation": "Betz v. Pneumo Abex, LLC, 2012 PA Super 413 (Pa. Super. 2012)", "ratio": "Rejected every-exposure doctrine as scientifically unsupported; epidemiological evidence did not establish causation below regulatory thresholds"}, {"citation": "Bostic v. Georgia-Pacific Corp., 447 S.W.3d 670 (Tex. 2014)", "ratio": "Excluded every-exposure testimony; required showing dose-response or quantified causal link"}]}',
ARRAY['cumulative-exposure doctrine', 'any-exposure-contributes'],
ARRAY['specific-causation', 'dose-response', 'biomarker', 'mechanism-of-action', 'bradford-hill-criteria']
